  "prompt": "Are there any other straight men diagnosed with histrionic personality disorder?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible for straight men to be diagnosed with **Histrionic Personality Disorder (HPD)**, though it is less commonly diagnosed in men compared to women. HPD is characterized by a pattern of excessive emotionality and attention-seeking behavior, and it can occur in individuals of any gender or sexual orientation.\n\nHistorically, HPD has been more frequently diagnosed in women, which may reflect societal biases or expectations about gender roles (e.g., women being socialized to express emotions openly). However, men can and do experience HPD, though they may exhibit symptoms in ways that align with societal expectations of masculinity, such as seeking attention through dominance, charisma, or dramatic behavior.\n\nUltimately, personality disorders are not limited by gender, and clinicians are increasingly mindful of avoiding gender biases in diagnosis. If you or someone you know is struggling with symptoms of HPD, seeking help from a mental health professional is important for accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment.",
